00:00:11.861 --> 00:00:15.587
 So this is a hotel room, just like the one I stay in. 

00:00:15.587 --> 00:00:17.731
 Sometimes I get bored. 

00:00:17.731 --> 00:00:21.158
 Such a room does not offer much entertainment. 

00:00:21.158 --> 00:00:25.687
 But for a hacker, she's a bit interesting, 

00:00:25.687 --> 00:00:28.136
 because that television is different from the home, 

00:00:28.136 --> 00:00:31.058
 it is a node on a network. 

00:00:31.058 --> 00:00:33.442
 That means I can mess with it. 

00:00:33.442 --> 00:00:37.024
 I plug a small device like this into my computer. 

00:00:37.024 --> 00:00:40.359
 It is an infrared transmitter-receiver with which I can send the codes 

00:00:40.359 --> 00:00:43.524
 that the TV remote can transmit and some other codes. 

00:00:43.524 --> 00:00:47.128
 Well, then I can watch movies for free. 

00:00:47.277 --> 00:00:49.275
 (Laughter) 

00:00:49.275 --> 00:00:53.681
 That doesn't really matter to me, but I can also play video games. 

00:00:54.749 --> 00:00:57.734
 Hey, but what is this? 

00:00:57.935 --> 00:01:01.010
 Not only can I do this for my TV in my hotel room, 

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:03.822
 I can also control the TV in your hotel room. 

00:01:03.822 --> 00:01:05.006
 (Laughter) 

00:01:05.006 --> 00:01:07.906
 So I can see what you are looking at, 

00:01:07.906 --> 00:01:10.892
 you know, that data on your TV 

00:01:10.892 --> 00:01:13.512
 when you surf the web on your hotel TV. 

00:01:13.512 --> 00:01:16.224
 I can see you doing it. 

00:01:17.182 --> 00:01:19.983
 Sometimes it is very interesting. 

00:01:19.983 --> 00:01:22.374
 Transfer of funds. 

00:01:22.712 --> 00:01:25.830
 Really large payment traffic. 

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.041
 You never know what people want to do 

00:01:28.041 --> 00:01:31.528
 while surfing the web from their hotel room. 

00:01:31.892 --> 00:01:34.633
 (Laughter) 

00:01:34.633 --> 00:01:38.122
 The point is I can tell if you're watching Disney or porn tonight. 

00:01:38.122 --> 00:01:40.451
 Is there anyone else in the Affinia hotel here? 

00:01:40.451 --> 00:01:42.614
 (Laughter) 

00:01:42.614 --> 00:01:46.502
 This is a project I worked on when we were trying to figure it out 

00:01:46.502 --> 00:01:49.292
 what about the security of wireless networks. 

00:01:49.292 --> 00:01:50.446
 It is called the 'Hackerbot'. 

00:01:50.446 --> 00:01:54.007
 This is a robot we built to find WiFi users. 

00:01:54.007 --> 00:01:57.358
 He drives over to them and shows them their passwords on the screen. 

00:01:57.358 --> 00:02:00.621
 (Laughter) 

00:02:00.621 --> 00:02:02.572
 We just wanted to build a robot, 

00:02:02.572 --> 00:02:05.143
 but we didn't know what to let him do, so - 

00:02:05.143 --> 00:02:07.338
 we made it a gun version. 

00:02:07.338 --> 00:02:09.131
 This is called the 'Sniper Yagi'. 

00:02:09.131 --> 00:02:11.890
 He sniffs long-distance passwords. 

00:02:11.890 --> 00:02:14.669
 I can see your wireless network from a mile away. 

00:02:14.669 --> 00:02:16.728
 This is a project I did with Ben Laurie 

00:02:16.728 --> 00:02:19.308
 worked to demonstrate passive surveillance. 

00:02:19.308 --> 00:02:22.171
 This is a map of the conference 

00:02:22.171 --> 00:02:24.427
 Computers, Freedom and Privacy. 

00:02:24.427 --> 00:02:28.774
 This conference took place in a hotel, and we placed 

00:02:28.774 --> 00:02:31.346
 a computer in every room 

00:02:31.346 --> 00:02:33.284
 which recorded all bluetooth traffic. 

00:02:33.284 --> 00:02:36.376
 We were able to hear telephone and laptop traffic from everyone 

00:02:36.376 --> 00:02:38.667
 record and correlate, 

00:02:38.667 --> 00:02:42.198
 and then I could make such a card for everyone at the conference. 

00:02:42.198 --> 00:02:45.541
 This is Kim Cameron, the Chief Privacy Architect at Microsoft. 

00:02:45.541 --> 00:02:46.468
 (Laughter) 

00:02:46.468 --> 00:02:49.139
 Without knowing it, 

00:02:49.139 --> 00:02:52.880
 I could see where he went everywhere 

